The better world is already here
COPENHAGEN – For centuries, optimists and pessimists have discussed the state of the world.
Pessimists see a world where more people mean less food, where increasing resource demand leads to plunder and war, and where the growing production capacity of the last decades brings about more pollution and global warming.
One of the holy texts of the current generation of pessimists, "The Limits to Growth," continues to influence the environmental movement today.
The optimists, on the other hand, claim that everything is getting better – human health, living standards, environmental quality, and so on.
They are seen by their opponents as "economists of abundance," who trust in the market supposedly capable of solving all problems.
But instead of picking out facts and stories that fit into a grand narrative of decline or progress, we should try to compare all areas of human existence to see if the world is really getting better or worse.
Exactly this is what I have tried to achieve together with 21 globally leading economists by developing a value list for the last 150 years.
In ten areas—ranging from health, education, war, gender ratio, air pollution, climate change, and biodiversity—to answer the same question: how high were the relative costs of this problem in each year from 1900 to 2013, including forecasts up to 2050.
Based on classical economic evaluations of all factors ranging from fatalities, health damage, and illiteracy to the destruction of wetlands up to higher hurricane risk through global warming, the economists show the costs of each individual problem.
To estimate the magnitude of the problem, it is compared with the resources available for its solution.
Through this, the size of the problem is clearly shown as a share of GDP.
And the trends since 1900 have been partly surprising.
Let's consider the gender inequality.
In essence, we excluded almost half of the world's population from production back then.
In 1900, only 15% of the workforce worldwide was female.
What losses arose from this small proportion?
Even though we account for the higher costs through women's education and acknowledge that someone must perform unpaid household work, the losses amounted to at least 17% of the global GDP in 1900.
Today, with a higher female labor participation rate and smaller income differences, the loss amounts to 7% – and is likely to fall to 4% by 2050.
It is likely to be surprising that climate change from 1900 to 2025 is expected to bring a growing net benefit – rising to as much as 1.5% of GDP annually.
This is due to the different effects of global warming. When it occurs only moderately, the benefits outweigh the costs.
On the other hand, the higher CO2 emissions were a boon for agriculture, as the gas acts as a fertilizer. This is the largest positive effect, amounting to 0.8% of GDP.
Moderate warming prevents more deaths from cold than it causes additional deaths from heat.
It also reduces heating demand more than it creates new cooling needs, which amounts to a benefit of about 0.4% of GDP.
On the other hand, warming leads to water scarcity, which costs about 0.2% of GDP, and has a negative impact on ecosystems like wetlands, resulting in a loss of about 0.1%.
As temperatures continue to rise, however, the costs increase and the benefits decrease, dramatically reducing the net benefit.
After 2070, global warming will impose net costs on the world, justifying cost-effective climate protection measures today and in the coming decades.
However, the value list also shows us that the greatest environmental problem worldwide is indoor air pollution, putting things into perspective.
Today, more than three million people die annually from indoor air pollution due to harmful gases from cooking and heating, equating to a loss of 3% of global GDP.
But in 1900, these costs amounted to 19% of GDP, and it is expected that they will fall to 1% by 2050.
The health indicators have improved the most worldwide.
By the late 18th century, human life expectancy had barely changed.
The gain since 1900 can hardly be overstated: At that time, the global life expectancy was 32 years, and today it is 69 years (and likely to be 76 years in 2050).
The biggest influencing factor was the decline in child mortality.
In 1970, for example, only 5% of infants were vaccinated against measles, tetanus, whooping cough, diphtheria, and polio.
In 2000, it was 85%, which saved three million lives every year – more than would have been saved by world peace throughout the entire 20th century.
This success has many parents.
The Gates Foundation and the GAVI Alliance have spent more than 2.5 billion USD on vaccines and promised an additional 10 billion.
Through the efforts of Rotary clubs, the World Health Organization, and many others, the number of polio cases has been reduced by 99% since 1979.
In economic terms, the costs of poor health at the beginning of the twentieth century amounted to astonishing 32% of global GDP.
They have fallen to around 11% and will halve again by 2050.
Even though the optimists are not entirely correct in all points (the loss of biodiversity in the twentieth century probably costs about 1% of GDP annually, and in some places much more), the overall picture is clear.
Most of the examined topics show improvements of 5-20% of GDP.
And the overall trend is even more pronounced.
Relative to the resources available to address them, the global problems have dramatically declined.
Of course, this does not mean that there are no problems left.
Even though they have become smaller in areas such as health, education, malnutrition, air pollution, gender inequality, and trade, they are still significant.
But realists should slowly get used to the idea that the world has significantly improved.
Furthermore, the value list shows us where the challenges for a better 2050 lie.
We should not base our view of the future on the most horrific stories or the loudest interest groups, but on objective assessments of where we can achieve the greatest improvements.
